  "Which species is most likely to exhibit r-selected characteristics?": "",
  "Elephant": "",
  "Human": "",
  "Bacteria": "",
  "Blue whale": "",
  "r-selected species like bacteria have rapid reproduction, many offspring, little parental care, and short lifespans. They thrive in unstable environments and can quickly exploit new resources.": "",
  "Which species is most likely to exhibit K-selected characteristics?": "",
  "Fruit fly": "",
  "Dandelion": "",
  "Mosquito": "",
  "K-selected species like elephants have few offspring, extensive parental care, long lifespans, and populations that tend to stabilize near carrying capacity. They thrive in stable environments.": "",
  "What does the 'doubling time' of a population refer to?": "",
  "The time for the death rate to double": "",
  "The time required for a population to double in size at its current growth rate": "",
  "The time for carrying capacity to double": "",
  "The time for the birth rate to double": "",
  "Doubling time is calculated as approximately 70 divided by the growth rate percentage (Rule of 70). A population growing at 2% per year doubles in about 35 years.": "",
  "In the logistic growth equation dN/dt = rN(K-N)/K, what does (K-N)/K represent?": "",
  "The fraction of carrying capacity still available for population growth": "",
  "The death rate of the population": "",
  "The immigration rate": "",
  "The birth rate of the population": "",
  "The term (K-N)/K represents the proportion of carrying capacity remaining. As N approaches K, this fraction approaches zero, slowing growth. When N equals K, growth stops completely.": "",
  "What typically happens when a population overshoots its carrying capacity?": "",
  "Nothing happens to the population": "",
  "The population crashes due to resource depletion, then may recover or stabilize": "",
  "The population continues to grow indefinitely": "",
  "Carrying capacity automatically increases to match": "",
  "Population overshoot occurs when growth exceeds what resources can sustain. The resulting resource depletion causes a population crash (dieback), after which the population may oscillate around K or collapse.": "",
  "What is exponential growth?": "",
  "A population that remains stable": "",
  "Population growth at a constant per capita rate, producing accelerating increases in population size over time": "",
  "Growth that occurs at a decreasing rate over time": "",
  "Growth that is limited by carrying capacity": "",
  "Exponential growth occurs when a population grows at a constant rate per individual per unit time. The result is ever-faster growth as the expanding population base multiplies at the same per capita rate.": "",
  "What does 'logistic growth' mean?": "",
  "Population growth that starts exponentially but slows as it approaches carrying capacity due to resource limitations": "",
  "Unlimited population growth with no constraints": "",
  "A steady decline in population over time": "",
  "Random population fluctuations": "",
  "Logistic growth incorporates environmental resistance. Growth starts rapidly when resources are abundant but decelerates as the population approaches carrying capacity and competition intensifies.": "",
  "What is 'carrying capacity (K)'?": "",
  "The maximum population size that an environment can sustain indefinitely given available resources": "",
  "The birth rate minus the death rate": "",
  "The minimum population size for survival": "",
  "The maximum growth rate of a population": "",
  "Carrying capacity (K) is the maximum population an environment can support long-term with its available resources. It can change over time as conditions change.": "",
  "What does 'r-selected species' refer to?": "",
  "Species with long lifespans and few offspring": "",
  "Species that reproduce rapidly with many offspring, little parental care, and short generation times": "",
  "Species that cannot reproduce": "",
  "Species that live near carrying capacity": "",
  "r-selected species are adapted for rapid reproduction and population growth (high r). They produce many offspring with little investment in each, enabling quick colonization of new or disturbed habitats.": "",
  "What does 'K-selected species' mean?": "",
  "Species with longer lifespans, fewer offspring, more parental care, and populations that tend to stabilize near carrying capacity": "",
  "Species that are always endangered": "",
  "Species that reproduce very quickly with no parental care": "",
  "Species that only live in tropical environments": "",
  "K-selected species invest heavily in fewer offspring, with long development, extensive parental care, and competitive traits. Their populations tend to fluctuate near the carrying capacity of their environment.": "",
  "What is meant by 'biotic potential'?": "",
  "The maximum reproductive rate of a population under ideal conditions with unlimited resources": "",
  "The minimum number of offspring needed for survival": "",
  "The actual observed growth rate": "",
  "The carrying capacity of a habitat": "",
  "Biotic potential is the theoretical maximum rate of population increase under perfect conditions. Real populations never achieve biotic potential because environmental resistance always limits growth.": "",
  "What does 'population overshoot' mean?": "",
  "When a population goes extinct": "",
  "When a population temporarily exceeds the carrying capacity of its environment": "",
  "When carrying capacity increases": "",
  "When a population grows slowly": "",
  "Population overshoot occurs when rapid growth pushes a population beyond carrying capacity. This depletes resources, and the population typically crashes back down, sometimes well below K.": "",
  "What is 'doubling time'?": "",
  "The time between two generations": "",
  "The time for resources to be depleted": "",
  "The time it takes for a population to reach carrying capacity": "",
  "The time required for a population to double in size, calculated approximately as 70 divided by the growth rate percentage": "",
  "Doubling time uses the Rule of 70: dividing 70 by the annual growth rate percentage gives the approximate number of years for a population to double. A 1% growth rate means doubling in about 70 years.": "",
  "What is 'zero population growth (ZPG)'?": "",
  "When a population has no births": "",
  "When a population has reached its maximum size ever": "",
  "When all organisms are the same age": "",
  "When births plus immigration equal deaths plus emigration, resulting in no net population change": "",
  "Zero population growth occurs when the population size is stable because additions (births + immigration) exactly balance losses (deaths + emigration), resulting in no net change.": "",
  "What does 'environmental resistance' mean?": "",
  "An organism's tolerance to temperature extremes": "",
  "The physical barriers in a habitat": "",
  "A species' resistance to pesticides": "",
  "The combined effect of all factors that limit population growth, preventing it from reaching biotic potential": "",
  "Environmental resistance includes all biotic and abiotic factors (predation, disease, competition, limited food, harsh climate) that collectively limit population growth below what biotic potential would allow.": "",
  "Bacteria placed in a nutrient-rich petri dish double every 20 minutes. Starting with 100 bacteria, how many would there be after 2 hours (6 doublings)?": "",
  "3,200": "",
  "600": "",
  "6,400": "",
  "1,200": "",
  "After 6 doublings: 100 x 2^6 = 100 x 64 = 6,400 bacteria. This exponential growth demonstrates how populations can explode when resources are not limiting.": "",
  "A deer population on an island was introduced with 10 individuals. For the first 15 years, the population grew rapidly to 500. Over the next 5 years, the deer ate most available vegetation, and the population crashed to 100. What growth pattern does this represent?": "",
  "Stable logistic growth at carrying capacity, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Zero population growth regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Normal exponential growth, based on conventional assumptions about population": "",
  "Overshoot and crash: the population exceeded carrying capacity, depleted resources, and then collapsed": "",
  "This is a classic overshoot-and-crash pattern. Without predators, the deer population grew past carrying capacity, overconsumed resources, and then crashed when food became insufficient.": "",
  "A country has a population of 50 million and a growth rate of 2% per year. Using the Rule of 70, approximately how long will it take for the population to reach 100 million?": "",
  "70 years": "",
  "35 years": "",
  "14 years": "",
  "140 years": "",
  "Using the Rule of 70: Doubling time = 70 / growth rate = 70 / 2 = 35 years. At a 2% growth rate, the population of 50 million would double to 100 million in approximately 35 years.": "",
  "An ecologist studying a lake ecosystem observes that a fish population initially grew exponentially after being introduced, but growth slowed and the population stabilized at about 10,000 fish. Two years later, a new nutrient-rich stream began flowing into the lake, and the fish population increased to 15,000 before stabilizing again. What happened?": "",
  "The 10,000 fish limit was not actually carrying capacity": "",
  "The fish switched from logistic to exponential growth permanently": "",
  "The fish evolved to need less food": "",
  "The new stream increased the lake's carrying capacity by adding resources, allowing the population to grow to a new, higher equilibrium": "",
  "Carrying capacity is not fixed; it depends on available resources. The nutrient-rich stream increased food availability (primary productivity), raising the lake's carrying capacity for fish from 10,000 to 15,000.": "",
  "Two species are introduced to separate identical habitats. Species A (a mouse) produces 8 offspring every 3 weeks with no parental care. Species B (a hawk) produces 2 offspring per year with extensive parental care. After 5 years, which species would likely have reached its carrying capacity first, and why?": "",
  "Species B, because hawks are better competitors": "",
  "Neither would reach carrying capacity in 5 years": "",
  "Species A, because its r-selected traits (rapid reproduction, short generation time) enable faster population growth toward K": "",
  "Both would reach carrying capacity at the same time": "",
  "The r-selected mouse population grows much faster due to short generation times and many offspring, reaching carrying capacity quickly. The K-selected hawk population grows slowly and would take much longer.": "",
  "The human population took approximately 200,000 years to reach 1 billion (around 1800), but only 200 more years to reach 8 billion. Which growth model best describes human population growth over the last few centuries, and what factors enabled it?": "",
  "Exponential growth, enabled by agricultural advances, medical improvements, and sanitation that reduced death rates while birth rates remained high": "",
  "Logistic growth, because human population has stabilized under most circumstances involving human": "",
  "Human population has actually been declining, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Linear growth at a steady rate when the interaction between human and population factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Human population has grown approximately exponentially since the Industrial Revolution, driven by increased food production (Green Revolution), modern medicine, improved sanitation, and reduced infant mortality.": "",
  "An invasive carp species is introduced to a river system. In the first year, the population doubles. In subsequent years, growth continues at a similar rate. Native fish populations begin to decline. A wildlife manager asks how quickly the carp population will reach problematic levels. What model should be used for the initial projection, and what are its limitations?": "",
  "The exponential model is appropriate for early invasion when resources are not limiting, but it will overestimate long-term growth because resource limitations and competition will eventually slow growth": "",
  "The logistic model, because all populations follow logistic growth, particularly when growth considerations are weighed against competing pressures": "",
  "Neither model can make predictions about invasive species, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these growth dynamics operate": "",
  "Linear growth models are always most accurate, since the relevant growth factors typically produce this outcome in practice": "",
  "During early invasion, exponential growth is appropriate because resources are abundant. However, the model becomes unrealistic as the population grows and competition, predation, and resource depletion begin to slow growth.": "",
  "A conservation biologist is managing a population of 200 endangered tortoises in a reserve. The tortoises are K-selected (live 100+ years, mature at age 20, lay 5-10 eggs per year). A drought kills 50% of the population. Compared to a similarly-sized r-selected species, how would recovery differ?": "",
  "Both would recover at the same rate": "",
  "The K-selected tortoises would recover much more slowly because of their low reproductive rate, long maturation time, and few offspring per year": "",
  "K-selected species never recover from population declines": "",
  "The tortoise population would recover faster than an r-selected species": "",
  "K-selected species recover slowly from population declines because they have low intrinsic growth rates (r), long generation times, and few offspring. An r-selected species could rebound within a few generations.": "",
  "A graph shows a population that grew rapidly, then oscillated above and below a line at 1,000 individuals before stabilizing. What does the line at 1,000 represent, and what caused the oscillations?": "",
  "The line represents carrying capacity (K), and the oscillations result from time lags between population overshoot, resource depletion, and recovery": "",
  "The oscillations indicate the population is going extinct": "",
  "The line represents the birth rate": "",
  "The line is the extinction threshold, and oscillations are random": "",
  "The line at 1,000 is carrying capacity. Oscillations occur because populations often overshoot K before resource depletion causes a decline, then undershoot before recovering. Over time, oscillations may dampen as the population approaches equilibrium.": "",
  "St. Matthew Island in Alaska had 29 reindeer introduced in 1944 with abundant lichens and no predators. By 1963, the population exploded to 6,000, then crashed to 42 by 1966. Using population growth models, explain what happened and what this teaches about sustainable populations.": "",
  "A disease killed the reindeer due to the well-established relationship between population trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "Without predators, the population grew exponentially past carrying capacity, overconsumed the slow-growing lichens, and suffered a catastrophic crash when food ran out": "",
  "The reindeer migrated to another island, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing population dynamics": "",
  "The reindeer exhibited stable logistic growth when the interaction between population and crash factors is taken into full account": "",
  "This is a textbook case of overshoot and crash. Without predators, exponential growth continued unchecked. The reindeer consumed lichens faster than they could regrow, leading to a devastating population crash that demonstrates why populations need regulatory mechanisms.": ""
